King Loingsech, in whose time the hymn is said to have been written, reigned (according to O’Flaherty's Chronology) from 695 to 704.

The legend in the Preface would seem to indicate that the first half of Cuchuimne’s life having been devoted to the study of literature, the second half was spent in profligacy. The obscure verses which tell of this are also found in the margin of the Dublin copy of the Annals of Ulster at the year 74⁶· where they are attributed, not to Adamnan‚ but to the Nurse of Cuchuimne. They are quoted, probably from the Annals of Ulster, by theFour Masters, and are also found in the margin of the Book of Fenagh (fol. 8).

Several points call for comment in these verses. Todd observes that in such a record of the weakness of Cuchuimne there is great internal evidence of truth. Co dmimne, ‘to the ridge’ plainly means ‘half-way'; [compare the Auru ll. 283, 286], but the phrase is a curious one.
